<subSubSection id="1F09227DCA177C718F305AC293A2B8DC" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="type">
<paragraph id="E82E635425A4D733447B3C552EF62690" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3E65F6E0181ACCFD088FF8B89DB357F1" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
Based on 
<taxonomicName id="A2B0015F425F1A4EE17F74CBF94D9D84" authorityName="Vvedensky" authorityYear="1927" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus subsp. hamadae" order="Solanales" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="subsericeus" subSpecies="hamadae">Convolvulus subsericeus subsp. hamadae</taxonomicName>
Vved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2F2E81200A8FEED69B761C296BE19F51" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="description">
<paragraph id="4D224D51E5FD9BA571DFD6E46B920F2F" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C6573DB6F43CEE8B1C9EE5BB9D58129D" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
Erect undershrub, intricately branched from the base to at least 40 cm; stems, thinly sericeous. Leaves 1-5 
<normalizedToken id="DF9EF3B172CAF3D0A3CBCF8A9325D951" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2 cm, linear-oblong, acute, base tapering into a long pseudopetiole, thinly adpressed pubescent and appearing greenish. Flowers 1 (-2) at the apex of rigid, straight, relatively slender woody peduncles 0.8-1.5 cm long; bracteoles minute, linear, c. 1 mm, pedicels 0.5-1 mm, bent at 90° to peduncle; sepals (3-) 4 (-5) 
<normalizedToken id="205BED334A7F32C468CE2A85742235BC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 mm, narrowly oblong, acute, densely pubescent; corolla (8-)10 mm, white, unlobed, broadly infundibuliform, midpetaline bands pilose, terminating in a tooth; ovary pilose. Capsule pilose, seeds pubescent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="158025BCBE421359D851F825307E4FD0" lastPageId="144" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="17ADEF2EF9B283140EFCB4CC3B00C6D7" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="00EB12A2A50A16B3C211669D34B93EAA" lastPageId="144" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
Kazakhstan (
<emphasis id="F1A59D42101EA6691BF796748780FDF1" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<pageBreakToken id="5453FB4A72AA6110159C7793F00EDAAC" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" start="start">Drobov</pageBreakToken>
</emphasis>
s.n. [3/8/1996], 
<emphasis id="E706662B68FF208B5CE9E84B45DA1938" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Krasheninnikov</emphasis>
158); Kyrgyzstan (
<emphasis id="58EA244EECFE0144B12FCB8622406876" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Knorring</emphasis>
115, 
<emphasis id="AFCCBFBA27F76C12BACFAB18C9A185FF" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Drobov</emphasis>
246); Uzbekistan (
<emphasis id="3E2DF837C8209330FBBEE5FCAB57BAAC" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Tishchenko</emphasis>
98, 
<emphasis id="CE917CAD5AAC1C10D6B728FAC79B6CE0" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Muravliansky</emphasis>
1932, 
<emphasis id="CCED66C989C65131D32093414CD07B5D" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Knorring</emphasis>
60); Tajikistan (
<emphasis id="A37D0B3803E3C04A33FEB404C7BDF08C" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Nikitin</emphasis>
167, s.n. [19/6/1936], 
<emphasis id="3460F00040489A61B08C811E54B0E385" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Knorring</emphasis>
129); Turkmenistan (
<emphasis id="55B6A1BB4AAB84BD9D42824A5995093A" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Litvinow</emphasis>
1647, 
<emphasis id="7A33AFC83E43CAAA1C57AF7F737A8D9D" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Sintenis</emphasis>
1285); Afghanistan (
<emphasis id="3C554EB21EBC0986FD27EC676C0F499C" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Aitchison</emphasis>
731); Iran (
<emphasis id="56A8FF624BE281ADC9F19E173E0C5042" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Pabot</emphasis>
DK 518). Most common in Uzbekistan.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AFE020D8E2EE300C23D8937369A41A72" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" type="notes">
<paragraph id="85A68184FECEB587F52B5BE91C5B4DEC" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6D4BDC7CEEDBDA8A324B336DF9EB39AC" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
The indumentum and corolla size suggests this lies between 
<taxonomicName id="F372F30DF8A6DAEDA44E271D898E8A25" authorityName="Ledeb., in Eichwald, Pl. Nov. Cauc. Casp. 11. 1831. (Eichwald" authorityYear="1831" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus erinaceus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erinaceus">
<emphasis id="D5E5AE2529C22E57D9C0DDD6A618A6BF" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus erinaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B1B4DCF25288DFE60411E80E1768BD25" authorityName="Schrenk, Enum. Pl. Nov. [F. E. L. Fischer &amp; C. A. Meyer] 1: 19. 1841. (Fischer and Meyer" authorityYear="1841" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericeus">
<emphasis id="87C9BDE86ED914B64A87DE847E5D201F" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus subsericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or more probably 
<taxonomicName id="6FC759BBB80E022AAA36B2CFBEF3B62C" authorityName="Boiss. &amp; Buhse, Nouv. Mem. Soc. Imp. Naturalises Moscou 12: 148. 1860. (Boissier and Buhse" authorityYear="1860" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus eremophilus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eremophilus">
<emphasis id="3B8B25E7B73362110D62E9EAEA63364B" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus eremophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, given the distribution of the three species. It has a laxer, less rigid appearance than 
<taxonomicName id="8099D33EC9BACDB1C68E045854051D99" authorityName="Ledeb., in Eichwald, Pl. Nov. Cauc. Casp. 11. 1831. (Eichwald" authorityYear="1831" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus erinaceus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erinaceus">
<emphasis id="4F98BBCAFFFB1B7798CD20E0F7D2966A" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus erinaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with branches less divaricate, the corolla is longer and unlobed and the sepals are acute, not obtuse. From 
<taxonomicName id="BFD3A70022550C5789B805BC85E3AE28" authorityName="Schrenk, Enum. Pl. Nov. [F. E. L. Fischer &amp; C. A. Meyer] 1: 19. 1841. (Fischer and Meyer" authorityYear="1841" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericeus">
<emphasis id="0847096A2A7CB19AB871A3B30F96D858" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus subsericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is distinguished by the shorter, pungent branches, flowers generally solitary and a little smaller, the sepals acute, not acuminate. From 
<taxonomicName id="ADD0783E4133CFEFCE33B4CFEBAC86B0" authorityName="Boiss. &amp; Buhse, Nouv. Mem. Soc. Imp. Naturalises Moscou 12: 148. 1860. (Boissier and Buhse" authorityYear="1860" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus eremophilus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eremophilus">
<emphasis id="2788CFA0282589A8ADFF37919FFF7B27" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus eremophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is distinguished by the sparse, adpressed indumentum of the stems and shorter corolla. A few specimens are completely glabrous, such as 
<emphasis id="459AB60B4F86FB2522FAE8F47FE2A692" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Botchantzev</emphasis>
468 from Uzbekistan, but seem to fit here best.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6C8A4EF6BD769166B26EA9D4E9B1E0D7" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<normalizedToken id="BAB6EE7A317C5F0B9120AF4F7CEA4F31" originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
treated this species as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4050781F61BF1F821AE2D34065391B71" authorityName="Ledeb., in Eichwald, Pl. Nov. Cauc. Casp. 11. 1831. (Eichwald" authorityYear="1831" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus erinaceus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erinaceus">
<emphasis id="58CBDF0AE80DB5381B9632B7DF8BE9E9" italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus erinaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the sepals and corolla are quite different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
